d="comment-130148"><div class="the-comment"><div class="comment-author">Shirley Rice</div><div class="comment-date">Sunday, April 14th, 2019</div><div class="comment-text">I am happy to read this. <br> <br>I was apprehensive when “The get big or get out” direction came out. I knew it would destroy small farmers and cause huge fields with no hedgerows for birds, etc, and monocultures. Monocultures require huge loads of chemicals that keep getting bigger. <br> <br>CAFOs are awful. One dairy CAFO near me recently removed another hedgerow for a more huge field and I saw them spreading liquid manure on the frozen field that will end up in the area streams and lakes. <br> <br>The farm where I lived and I sold is tilled by a soybean and corn farmer, solely with chemicals. The land sits naked to the winds in winter and blows away. <br> <br>A dairy farm down the road has gone all grass fed and the beef farmer around the corner has gone grass fed. No more corn behind the hedgerow from me with many chemicals in my well. I feel much safer and I’m grateful. <br> <br>I buy local organic vegetables and eggs.  Many of the veggies are grown under cover. Organic crops are usually grown in small lots and the farmers are mindful of other necessary life, as important as our own to the earth. I do not use herbicides or pesticides on my rural property. I was suspicious of GMOs from the beginning and their companion pesticides and have eschewed them.</div><div class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-130148' data-commentid="130148" data-postid="31136" data-belowelement="comment-130148" data-respondelement="respond" aria-label='Reply to Shirley Rice'>Reply</a></div></div></div></li><!-- #comment-## --></ol><div class="break1"></div></div></div></div></div><div id="article-bottom"><div class='ctx-module-container ctx_shortcode_placement ctx-clearfix'></div><div class="break4"></div><div id="trending"><h3>TRENDING</h3><div class="pop-posts"><ul><li id="wpp-2" 